<font color="#FF0000">REMEMBER OTHES AS WELL.</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 19 12:39:56 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Not only were there ANZAC forces in Vietnam, but there were a number of Korean forces there too.  Some protesters I've heard from don't realize that there were a number of forces there.<br><br>
I didn't have much contact with the ANZAC forces, but I was in the ER at 1st Med Battalian, 1st Marine Division, DaNang on TDY from the Air Force for a few weeks.  And I was there when Korean casualties came in.  <br><br>
Usually, when American casualties came into the ER, we wouldn't know if it was serious or not.  Sometimes we'd have a call for serious casualties, and the person would come in with a flesh wound.  Sometimes, we'd be surprised with a very serious situation when we thought it was routine.<br><br>
But whenever the Koreans (ROK) would call in with casualties, we knew it was serious.  They simply didn't come in unless it was very necessary.  One time, a Korean patrol had run into a booby trap, and the soldier had been hit across his entire side.  He came in smoking a cigarette, and he accomplished the transfer from the stretcher to the X-Ray table, with us stabilizing his leg.  When we got the pictures of his leg back, he had what looked like a bed spring sitting against his fractured femur, and his ankle was so seriously damaged that I think he lost it.<br><br>
Another Korean soldier came in after an earthen pot exploded in his face.  He needed eye surgery, and I think it went okay.  The doctor told us to uncross his legs so they wouldn't go to sleep when he was under anasthesia.  With the language difficulties, he didn't want the poor fellow to think he'd lost his leg during the surgery.<br><br>
Later, three Korean soldiers came in after being ambushed.  They were very concerned about one of their members who was unconscious and not breathing.  This man was still warm, but the doctor declared him dead of asphyxia from a broken wind pipe.  We could fix that now, but this guy was lost.  When his buddies asked about it, all I could do in my limited Korean is say &quot;I don't know.&quot;  But the man died.<br><br>
This is my way of saying to all the forces from all the lands that served there, thank you for that service and that sacrifice.  Yours is every bit as great as anyone else's.  Our wall doesn't do justice to the totality of the situation.  <br><br>
We also need to remember that perhaps the greatest sacrifice came from the indigenous people, whom we were there to help, and some of whom we enlisted to help us. They lost not only their livelyhood, but also their land, their freedom, their prosperity and their very sense of self.  Vietnamese, Laotians, and Cambodians suffered the greatest effects of these wars.  Some of these people are now our citizens, and none of their names are on the Wall.<br><br>
Perhaps, when all is said and done, a similar wall should be built in Vietnam, with all the names on it from all sides.  Only then will the immensity of the situation be fully realized.  Imagine, a wall with names on it, stretching from horizon to horizon. Maybe then we could begin to grasp the tragedy that is war.
